    <h2>Section A: Attempt any two questions.</h2><h3>Question 1</h3>
<div><p><p>Why model of a system is built? What is static model? Differentiate between static and dynamic mathematical models in simulation.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>A <strong>model</strong> of a system is built to represent and simulate the behavior of the real-world system to analyze, understand, predict, or control its performance. Models are used in various fields such as engineering, physics, economics, biology, and more. They can be physical, conceptual, or mathematical representations of a system.</p>
<p>A <strong>static model</strong> is a type of mathematical model that represents the relationships and dependencies among variables at a specific point in time, without considering the changes over time. In other words, it captures the system&#8217;s state or structure without accounting for the dynamic aspects. Static models are often used to analyze equilibrium conditions or to study the steady-state behavior of a system. Example: Supply and demand model, class diagrams etc.</p>
<div class="table_wrapper" style="overflow-x:auto;"><table style="border-collapse: collapse; width: 96.1538%; height: 144px;">
<tbody>
<tr style="height: 24px;">
<td style="width: 46.5385%; text-align: center; height: 24px;"><strong>Static Model</strong></td>
<td style="width: 49.6153%; text-align: center; height: 24px;"><strong>Dynamic Model</strong></td>
</tr>
<tr style="height: 24px;">
<td style="width: 46.5385%; text-align: center; height: 24px;">Does not consider the changes over time; focuses on the system&#8217;s state at a specific point in time.</td>
<td style="width: 49.6153%; text-align: center; height: 24px;">Captures the evolution of the system over time, representing how variables change with respect to time.</td>
</tr>
<tr style="height: 24px;">
<td style="width: 46.5385%; text-align: center; height: 24px;">Typically involves algebraic equations that express relationships between variables at a specific moment.</td>
<td style="width: 49.6153%; text-align: center; height: 24px;">Involves differential equations or difference equations to represent the rate of change of variables over time.</td>
</tr>
<tr style="height: 24px;">
<td style="width: 46.5385%; text-align: center; height: 24px;">Suitable for analyzing steady-state conditions, examining system structure, or studying equilibrium.</td>
<td style="width: 49.6153%; text-align: center; height: 24px;">Used for simulating and understanding the time-dependent behavior of a system, predicting future states, or studying transient responses.</td>
</tr>
<tr style="height: 24px;">
<td style="width: 46.5385%; text-align: center; height: 24px;">Represents the system at a snapshot in time, providing a snapshot of the system&#8217;s configuration.</td>
<td style="width: 49.6153%; text-align: center; height: 24px;">Represents how the system evolves over time, offering insights into its dynamic behavior.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
</div>
<h3>Question 2</h3>
<div><p><p>What is storage in GPSS? Describe the blocks associated to storage in GPSS. A machine tool in a manufacturing shop is turning out parts at the rate off one every 5 minutes. As they are finished the parts go on an inspector who takes 10 ± 3 minutes to examine each one and rejects 10% of the parts. Represent the system in GPSS using the concept of facility and run the simulation for 500 parts.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p align="left">A Storage Entity is associated with several storage units that are allocated and returned by Transactions. Storage Entities can be used as &#8220;token pools&#8221; for controlling the flow of Transactions in the model.</p>
<p align="left"><strong>ENTER</strong> and <strong>LEAVE</strong> Blocks are used to update the statistics associated with a Storage Entity and several SNAs are available that return derived statistics.</p>
<p align="left">Storage entities must be defined by a STORAGE Command.</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>ENTER</strong> block:
<p align="left">When a Transaction ENTERs a Storage Entity, it utilizes or occupies one or more storage units of the Storage Entity. A Transaction is denied entry into an ENTER Block if its storage demand cannot be met. Such a Transaction comes to rest on the Delay Chain of the Storage Entity. Then it must wait until other Transactions free enough storage by entering LEAVE Blocks. Storage capacity may be released by any Transaction, even if it had not previously ENTERed the Storage Entity. However, if more capacity is released than was declared in the STORAGE Command an Error Stop occurs.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-29703 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/enter.jpg?resize=181%2C61&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="181" height="61"></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>LEAVE</strong> block: When a Transaction enters a LEAVE Block and gives up one or more storage units, other Transactions are sought that can have their storage demands satisfied. A &#8220;first-fit-with-skip&#8221; discipline is used to schedule Transactions that are waiting. This means that each Transaction on the Delay Chain is tested for fit in the Storage Entity, starting with the highest priority. If a fit is found, the Transaction is removed from the Storage Delay Chain, allowed to enter the ENTER Block, and placed on the CEC behind its priority peers. Then the next Transaction on the Storage Delay Chain is tested.</li>
</ul>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="size-full wp-image-29704 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/leave.jpg?resize=181%2C61&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="181" height="61"></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone  wp-image-29706" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/gpss.jpg?resize=415%2C606&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="415" height="606"></p>
</div>
<h3>Question 3</h3>
<div><p><p>What are the two main properties of random numbers? Test whether the 3rd, 7th, 11th, and so on numbers in the sequence in the following random number sample are auto-correlated. (Z<sub>α</sub>=0.05 and Z<sub>0.025</sub>=1.96)</p>
<p>0.12 0.01 0.23 0.28 0.89 0.31 0.64 0.28 0.83 0.93 0.99 0.15 0.33 0.35 0.91 0.41 0.60 0.27 0.75 0.88 0.68 0.49 0.05 0.43 0.95 0.58 0.19 0.36 0.69 0.87</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>The two main properties of random numbers are independence and uniformity.</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><strong>Independence: </strong>Independence refers to the lack of correlation or relationship between successive random numbers in a sequence. In an ideal random sequence, the occurrence or value of one number should not provide information about the occurrence or value of the next number.</li>
<li><strong>Uniformity: </strong>Uniformity means that each number in the sequence has an equal chance of being selected. In a uniformly distributed random sequence, the probability of any specific value occurring is the same for all values.</li>
</ol>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone  wp-image-29709" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/SmartSelect_20240204_180216_CamScanner.jpg?resize=497%2C755&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="497" height="755"></p>
</div>
<h2>Section B: Attempt any eight questions.</h2><h3>Question 4</h3>
<div><p><p>Explain Markov chain with suitable example.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>If the future states of a process are independent of the past and depend only on the present, the process is called a Markov process. A discrete state Markov process is called a Markov chain. A Markov Chain is a random process with the property that the next state depends only on the current state.</p>
<p>Markov chains are used to analyze trends and predict the future. (Weather, stock market, genetics, product success, etc.</p>
<p><strong>Formally,</strong></p>
<p>A Markov chain is a sequence of random variables X<sub>1</sub>, X<sub>2</sub>, X<sub>3</sub>, &#8230; with the Markov property, namely that, given the present state, the future and past states are independent.</p>
<p>\(P(X_{n+1} = j|X_n = i_n, x_{n-1} = i_{n-1}, . . ., x_0 = i_0) = P(X_{n+1} = j|X_n = i_n)\)</p>
<p>The conditional probability above gives us the probability that a process in state i<sub>n</sub> at time n moves to i<sub>n+1</sub> at time n + 1. We call this the transition probability for the Markov chain. If the transition probability does not depend on the time n, we have a stationary Markov chain, with transition probabilities</p>
<p>\(P_{ij} = P(X_{n+1} = j|X_n = i)\)</p>
<p>Now we can write down the whole Markov chain as a matrix P:</p>
<p>\(P = \begin{bmatrix}<br />
P_11 &amp; P_12 &amp; &#8230;. &amp; P_1n\\<br />
P_21 &amp; P_22 &amp; &#8230;. &amp; P_2n\\<br />
. &amp; . &amp; . &amp; .\\<br />
. &amp; . &amp; . &amp; .\\<br />
. &amp; . &amp; . &amp; .\\<br />
P_n1 &amp; P_n2 &amp; &#8230;. &amp; P_nn\\<br />
\end{bmatrix}\)</p>
<p>Example:</p>
<p>Weather Problem:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>raining today  ⇒ 40 % rain tomorrow</li>
</ul>
<p>⇒ 60 % no rain tomorrow</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>not raining today  ⇒ 20 % rain tomorrow</li>
</ul>
<p>⇒ 80 % no rain tomorrow</p>
<p>What will be the probability if today is not raining then not rain the day after tomorrow?</p>
<p><i>Markov chain diagram:</i></p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="size-full wp-image-10953 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/download-2.png?resize=334%2C145&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="334" height="145"></p>
<p>\(P^2 = \begin{pmatrix}0.4 &amp; 0.6 \\ 0.2 &amp; 0.8\end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix}0.4 &amp; 0.6 \\ 0.2 &amp; 0.8\end{pmatrix}\)</p>
<p>\(= \begin{pmatrix}0.16 + 0.12 &amp; 0.24 + 0.48 \\ 0.08 + 0.16 &amp; 0.12 + 0.64\end{pmatrix}\)</p>
<p>\(= \begin{pmatrix}0.28 &amp; 0.72 \\ 0.24 &amp; 0.76\end{pmatrix}\)</p>
<p>Thus, the probability of not being rainy the day after tomorrow is 0.76.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 5</h3>
<div><p><p>What are steps involved in simulation study? Explain.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><strong>Problem Formulation:</strong>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Clearly define the problem that needs to be addressed using simulation. Identify the objectives and goals of the study.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Setting of Objectives &amp; Overall Project Plan:</strong>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Establish specific objectives for the simulation study and create an overall project plan outlining the timeline, resources, and milestones.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Model Conceptualization:</strong>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Develop a conceptual model that represents the system being simulated. This involves deciding on the structure and components of the model.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Data Collection:</strong>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Gather relevant data to support the model. This includes parameters, inputs, and initial conditions. The data should be accurate and representative of the real system.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Model Translation:</strong>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Translate the conceptual model into a formal representation, often using mathematical equations or computational algorithms. Implement the model in a simulation environment.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Verification:</strong>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Ensure that the simulation model accurately represents the conceptual model by checking its correctness. Verification involves validating the coding and logic of the model.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Validation:</strong>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Validate the simulation model by comparing its outputs to real-world data. This step ensures that the model behaves realistically and provides valid insights into the system.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Experimental Design:</strong>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Plan the experiments or scenarios that will be simulated. Define the input variations, conditions, and factors to be tested. Set up the simulation&#8217;s boundary conditions.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Production Runs:</strong>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Execute the simulation with the specified inputs and conditions. Collect data on the system&#8217;s behavior, performance, and other relevant output measures during the production runs.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Repetition of Runs:</strong>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Conduct multiple simulation runs to assess the variability and robustness of the model. Repetition helps ensure that the results are consistent and reliable.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Documentation &amp; Report:</strong>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Document the simulation study, including the model details, assumptions, data sources, and results. Generate a comprehensive report summarizing the findings and insights.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Implementation:</strong>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Implement the recommendations or decisions based on the simulation results. This may involve changes to the real-world system or the adoption of specific strategies.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
